      "died_year": 1912,
      "died_place": "Nottingham",
      "bio": "Samuel Waite Johnson (b. 1831, Bramley, Yorkshire; d. Nottingham, 14 January 1912) was one of the foremost locomotive designers of the steam age.\n\nJohnson was educated at Leeds Grammar School. He went on to become the Chief Mechanical Engineer and Locomotive Superintendent of the Midland Railway Company from 1873 to 1903.\n\nThe steam locomotives he designed for Midland Railway are considered to be some of the finest steam engines ever built. His designs won the Gold Medal at the Saltaire Exhibition in 1877 and the Grand Prix at the Paris Exhibition in 1889. His most notable designs included the Prince of Wales class 4-2-2 engines built between 1887 and 1893, and the \"Midlands Compounds\" \u2014 the Midland Railway 1000 Class 3 cylinder compound 4-4-0s (1902+).\n\nHis Midland Railway 4-2-2 (\"Spinner\") locomotive No. 673 remains on display at the National Railway Museum in York.\n\nHe was President of the Institution of Mechanical Engineers in 1898. He was also honoured by the Khedive of Egypt for his contribution to the development of the Egyptian railway system.",
